menuconfig MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY
	bool "On-device screen UI (CFB)"
	select DISPLAY
	select CHARACTER_FRAMEBUFFER
	help
	  Render a small on-device status UI on the board's monochrome display
	  using Zephyr's Character Framebuffer (CFB). It reads node/state data
	  from the existing Meshtastic C getters, so no phone app or shell is
	  required.

	  The board must provide a `chosen { zephyr,display }` node (e.g. the
	  SSD1306 OLED on the Heltec WiFi LoRa 32 V4); its driver (CONFIG_SSD1306
	  and friends) auto-enables from that devicetree node. Intended for small
	  monochrome panels such as 128x64 and 160x80.

	  A read-only status UI: a launcher menu plus a few pages (device info,
	  node list, stack status). With a board button (alias sw0) it is
	  navigable; without one it falls back to auto-cycling the pages on a
	  timer.

if MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_BUTTON
	bool "Navigate with the board button (sw0)"
	default y
	select INPUT
	help
	  Drive the UI from the board's user button, wired via a gpio-keys node
	  aliased as sw0 (the PRG/USER key on the Heltec V4). A short press moves
	  to the next item (the highlight cycles in a loop); a long press
	  confirms the highlighted choice. In a page, the footer offers Back
	  (return to the launcher) and Next (advance to the next page).

	  Selects the input subsystem; the gpio-keys driver auto-enables from the
	  devicetree node. If the board has no sw0 alias, or this is disabled, the
	  UI auto-cycles its pages on a timer instead.

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_REFRESH_MS
	int "Screen refresh interval (ms)"
	default 1000
	range 100 10000
	help
	  How often the current page is redrawn. Live counters (TX/RX, RSSI,
	  uptime) update at this cadence. Button presses are handled immediately,
	  independent of this interval.

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_LONGPRESS_MS
	int "Long-press threshold (ms)"
	default 600
	range 200 3000
	depends on MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_BUTTON
	help
	  How long the button must be held to count as a long press (confirm)
	  rather than a short press (next). The long press fires at this threshold
	  while the button is still held, for immediate feedback.

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_TIMEOUT_SECONDS
	int "Blank the screen after N seconds idle (0 = never)"
	default 30
	range 0 3600
	depends on MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_BUTTON
	help
	  With no button activity for this long, the panel is blanked to save
	  power. The next button press wakes it without also navigating. Set 0 to
	  keep the screen on permanently.

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_PAGE_SECONDS
	int "Seconds per page before auto-advancing (no-button fallback)"
	default 4
	range 1 60
	help
	  When no button is available (MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_BUTTON=n or the board
	  has no sw0 alias), the UI cycles through its pages on a timer. This sets
	  how long each page stays on screen.

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_STACK_SIZE
	int "Display thread stack size"
	default 2048
	help
	  Stack for the dedicated screen-refresh thread. It only calls CFB and the
	  Meshtastic getters, so a couple of KB is plenty.

config MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY_PRIORITY
	int "Display thread priority"
	default 10
	help
	  Preemptible priority of the screen-refresh thread. Kept below the radio
	  and packet-processing work so drawing never starves the mesh.

endif # MESHTASTIC_DISPLAY
